			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Diggo's guide to player bartering</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:ronjaffe@bellsouth.net">Diggo McDiggity</a> | 
		            1/4/2000 9:57:47 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Sooner or later, you will either have the money for an item that you really want or have an item that you really want to sell. Now the time comes to barter with other players. Welcome to the world of bartering!<P>
Now bartering can be exciting or it can be a headache depending upon your perspective. Invariably, because most people don't know what it is like in the real world to have your own business, they may complain and whine about the prices you are charging, or what you offer for a particular item. To these folks, I say, "Screw off..if you don't want the item, don't buy it...or in other words, "You are not a member of the buying guild..Begon."<P>
There is definitely an economy present in Everquest. Many people who complain the most feel that a particular item has a specific price...period. No matter where you are, who wants to buy it, what the item is, they feel that this particular item sells only for this price and that's all there is to it. If you advertise it for more, they complain. If you advertise it for less...or a lot less, they will buy it. You will never hear these people say, "Oh, you are not charging enough for that item."<P>
Eventually, as you sift through all the items that people are selling, you will see certain things always for about the same price. While that may establish a price for that item, it doesn't necessarily mean you have to sell it for that. The price of an item in a normal economy (which should include Everquest) is set by supply and demand. The more of an item that there is, the less it sells for. Conversely, rare items generally sell for more. This is applied to Everquest thusly:
Consider that unique or rare items will generally sell for less if you are in a zone where those items are dropped. For example, there is a ring that is dropped by the Dervish Cutthroat mobs that is a +2 Dexterity and +1 AC ring. Now any ring like that that a jeweler makes with same stats sells for around 2-3plat. But because this ring is dropped so much, the price is deflated. These typically sell for around 1/5 of that price, usually for a few gold. Now, take a backpack or two of these rings to someplace where there are NO dervish cutthroats, and you will be able to sell these for the 2-3plat that crafted rings go for.<P>
Bartering is a skill of its own, really, one that can make you a tremendous amount of money during those times when you are battling for experience points. Bartering allows you to see different cities, different continents, and meet different people. It's fun setting up shop in a new area with packs full of things that can only be found on other continents knowing you will leave with a couple hundred plat more than you started with for an hour or two's worth of work.<P>
Selling your own crafted items<P>
Hopefully at some point you will have undertaken skill training in one of the dozen or so trades built into everquest.  You might like to learn tailoring or jewelcraft or make some really good bows and arrows. Well, these skills take a tremendous amount of time and money to learn and the items you eventually are able to craft should provide a good living for you. Many people who bitch and complain about the prices people charge for crafted items have no idea how much time and money is really spent to increase one's skill.  As a master fletcher, people dont realize that everytime I attempt to craft a darkwood bow and fail, I am out over 300 platinum pieces.  You have to build that loss into your price as well as the time and cost of your training to get there. <P>
With most skills, as you learn, you sell most of your crafted items back to the merchants at a loss. That money adds up especially when you reach the master level. At the highest level of fletching, I take about 10-15 plat loss PER 20 arrows that I craft considering what I spend and what I sell them back to merchant for. Someone has to pay for that. The person who just wants a good bow doesn't want to have to worry about the time and cost invovled in learning to fletch. He just wants to complete the transaction for a new bow in 30 seconds and he is gone. Nothing wrong with the price reflecting that time and money put into learning the skill.<P>
How much to charge for crafted items<P>
Some people will disagree with me here, but as a general rule, in a normal situation, I will double my cost on parts for a given item that I fashion.(In the real world this is called Keystoning) A +2 Wisdom ring may cost me about 1 plat to make and I sell for 2-3plat. Now, this practice varies greatly due to several factors that have to be taken into consideration:<P>
1. How rare is the item you have crafted? If there are lots of them around, then your price may not be double. If you are the only one selling a given item, then you may charge even more.<BR>
2. How complicated is the item to make? For any given skill there are less people able to make the upper-end items. That extra skill is worth something. Again, your price may take that into consideration.<BR>
3. How much demand is there? If everyone has to have something, demand will allow you to charge more for a particular item.<BR>
4. Lastly how far away are the parts to make a given item? Examples are bows and arrows. In certain areas there may not be a bow or arrow supply place anywhere near, so people would gladly pay a higher price for arrows and bows so they don't have to go back themselves and waste time travelling. You are selling items but are also selling a service...a delivery service in one respect.<P>
The bottom line is that despite what whining folks claim, there is NO PRICE GOUGING in Everquest. Feel free to charge whatever you want for items, but understand that pricing your items fairly and competitively will allow you to sell more, more quickly. Price gouging would be if you were highly overcharged for something that you could not do without such as food or water. No one is being forced to buy your items so again, charge what  you feel is fair and you will do well.<P>
I hope this has helped a bit. I am writing another guide on the importance of Charisma when buying and selling.<P>
Good Luck!<P>
Diggy McDiggity/20th Druid/Tribunal Server
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
